<paragraph id="40DB3893EACD2461B00FBEE1F94993D6" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CEA7214828DD60C6760D2CF642D1A4D0" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The limited representation in herbaria, as well as the low abundance in the field, makes the 
<taxonomicName id="C495184534466BCE5ED4A135AFE1F760" authorityName="Phil., Anales Museo Nacional, Botanica 2: 64" authorityYear="1891" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum polyphyllum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polyphyllum">
<emphasis id="2597B3CD18A9B5CD8329F18BE2DEBE2A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Solanum polyphyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a candidate for threatened status. Due to its distribution in the two known locations of Compe and Pachica it is Data Deficient, pending further field work. 
<taxonomicName id="31EFCEF05613D98E54C066C381CDF9B4" authorityName="Phil., Anales Museo Nacional, Botanica 2: 64" authorityYear="1891" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum polyphyllum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polyphyllum">
<emphasis id="A4C63FBA842483F8B51F300496B0B785" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Solanum polyphyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
potentially could be found in Isluga National Park but new surveys are required to corroborate its presence in this protected area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9212DFB3707FF79A189E9BF49F596EA4" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A6DB5ECE1FE5C71B247D4BC0E17C0766" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C1977A4669994B98CCC83C062BB6557" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
In its broadly decurrent leaves on the stem, 
<taxonomicName id="702C15ADE34AD71FCD591EC8A13148C0" genus="S." lsidName="S. polyphyllum" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="polyphyllum">
<emphasis id="3DA43FD34C206C35B20A8C3D96027A11" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">S. polyphyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="62B2AD408A240B3BCDB008C72FCADCB0" genus="S." lsidName="S. paposanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="paposanum">
<emphasis id="06FE93A39CA0036AC3998401BB5DFB76" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">S. paposanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Phil., which grows both in 
<normalizedToken id="FE25287486252BD42359DE78B9C8549F" originalValue="Perú">Peru</normalizedToken>
and in Chile, from 200-3500 m elevation. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="872C6D825083155595D2C68CAEDB25F7" genus="S." lsidName="S. paposanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="paposanum">
<emphasis id="50B8781C01F22CEA00E61FDBB0C0BCB5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">S. paposanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its entire (versus margins with 4-5 acute lobes in 
<taxonomicName id="F713BFE3469202F303DDDB7F943B04CA" genus="S." lsidName="S. paposanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="paposanum">
<emphasis id="C80E0B7E86B2597A1AA541AEA4AC4D91" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">S. paposanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and glabrous leaves (versus moderately pubescent adaxially and velutinous abaxially in 
<taxonomicName id="F2CECC0458F95E1EF104A14F8ACA8B1E" genus="S." lsidName="S. paposanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="paposanum">
<emphasis id="8B98D54AA16E4F9415F87C505DDBBE0E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">S. paposanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C9033DE37D3D3D8EC4582AC03AF26940" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName id="712073C2D6D9E8859EB641D201B91B57" authorityName="Phil., Anales Museo Nacional, Botanica 2: 64" authorityYear="1891" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum polyphyllum" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polyphyllum">
<emphasis id="B5B7889359B49AD303AD4C6FF66A96AD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Solanum polyphyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by Rodulfo Amando Philippi based on specimens collected in Pachica (
<geoCoordinate id="C0D2C301C025187753882B62EA9B2E6E" degrees="19" direction="south" minutes="51" orientation="latitude" precision="15" seconds="58" value="-19.866112">19°51'58&quot;S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="45B32A7712D027EB239B58A6AD1971D2" degrees="69" direction="west" minutes="25" orientation="longitude" precision="15" seconds="56" value="-69.43222">69°25'56&quot; W</geoCoordinate>
, 1622 m alt.) by Carlos Rahmer during a journey to 
<normalizedToken id="AFF76F45A5F5403FF06C41ACB5EC1ED8" originalValue="Tarapacá">Tarapaca</normalizedToken>
made in 1885. Of this gathering, two duplicates are conserved in SGO. We designate as lectotype SGO000004586 (acc.#55603, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="218A9F76C28FBD3F9E779929FF0821C8" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Solanum polyphyllum Phil. (lectotype: C. Rahmer s. n., SGO 000004586 acc.  55603)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.156.53703.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/444123" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">1</figureCitation>
), which is very complete and has the handwritten label of R.A. Philippi. The duplicate specimen (SGO000004587, acc.#42779) has a label written by Federico Philippi (son of R.A. Philippi) who also participated in the 1885 expedition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4B68236C2D795DE3526C15D02370BE5C" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The rediscovery of this remarkable plant provides an opportunity to promote more intensive fieldwork in the 
<normalizedToken id="8DB3FDEC191F902571E27514C45590D7" originalValue="Tarapacá">Tarapaca</normalizedToken>
cordillera, at the transition belt between the desert and precordillera vegetation types, where vegetation greening seems to occur more often due to regional climate change. Despite the sparse vegetation that dominates in the Atacama, new botanical discoveries in different plant families are currently happening, as in 
<taxonomicName id="254D11EDB57639D7FC124642982DCF0E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName id="3A23CA73D14A33112226556F6F1428FD" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Senecio" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Senecio" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="771D081376BFDB03AEB26656B183EE52" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Senecio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
